= Food, Feeding, and Digestion

- *High Metabolic Rate*: Requires large amounts of food. Small birds eat more relative to body mass.
- *Beaks*: Adapted to food habits (e.g., generalized, seed cracking, probing, straining, tearing meat).

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-27-11").path, width: 80%),
  caption: images.at("figure-27-11").caption
)

- *Digestive System*:
  - *Crop*: Storage; produces "crop milk" in pigeons.
  - *Stomach*:
    - *Proventriculus*: Secretes gastric juice.
    - *Gizzard*: Grinds food (keratinized plates, grit).
  - *Ceca*: Fermentation chambers in herbivores.
  - *Cloaca*: Common exit for digestive, excretory, and reproductive systems.

= Circulatory and Respiratory Systems

- *Circulatory System*:
  - 4-chambered heart (complete separation of pulmonary/systemic).
  - Right aortic arch persists (unlike left in mammals).
  - Nucleated erythrocytes.
- *Respiratory System*:
  - *Parabronchi*: Tubelike lungs for continuous air flow.
  - *Air Sacs*: 9 interconnecting sacs; allow one-way flow of air through lungs (takes 2 cycles for one breath).
  - Highly efficient for high altitude and metabolic demands; also cools the body.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-27-12").path, width: 80%),
  caption: images.at("figure-27-12").caption
)

= Excretory System

- *Kidneys*: Metanephric; excrete *uric acid* (semisolid, water conservation).
- *Salt Glands*: Located above eyes in marine birds; excrete excess salt (NaCl).

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-27-13").path, width: 80%),
  caption: images.at("figure-27-13").caption
)

= Nervous and Sensory Systems

- *Brain*: Well-developed cerebellum (coordination) and optic lobes (vision). Enlarged dorsal ventricular ridge in cerebrum (instinctive behavior).

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-27-14").path, width: 80%),
  caption: images.at("figure-27-14").caption
)

- *Senses*:
  - *Vision*: Keenest in animal kingdom. Large eyes, *pecten* (nutrients), *foveae* (sharp focus). Some see UV light.
  - *Hearing*: Good sensitivity; cochlea shorter than mammals.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-27-15").path, width: 80%),
  caption: images.at("figure-27-15").caption
)

= Flight

- *Aerodynamics*:
  - Wing is an airfoil (cambered).
  - *Lift*: Generated by negative pressure on upper surface and positive pressure below.
  - *Slots*: *Alula* and gaps between primaries prevent stalling at low speeds/high angles of attack.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-27-16").path, width: 80%),
  caption: images.at("figure-27-16").caption
)

- *Flapping Flight*: Primaries provide thrust; secondaries provide lift.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-27-17").path, width: 80%),
  caption: images.at("figure-27-17").caption
)

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-27-18").path, width: 80%),
  caption: images.at("figure-27-18").caption
)

- *Wing Types*:
  - *Elliptical*: Maneuverability (sparrows, doves). Low aspect ratio, slotted.
  - *High Aspect Ratio*: High speed (swallows) or dynamic soaring (albatrosses). Long, narrow, no slots.
  - *High-Lift*: Static soaring, carrying heavy loads (hawks, eagles). Broad, slotted wings.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-27-19").path, width: 80%),
  caption: images.at("figure-27-19").caption
)

= Migration and Navigation

- *Migration*: Seasonal movement between breeding and wintering grounds.
  - Stimulus: Lengthening days (photoperiod) stimulate pituitary and gonads.
- *Navigation*:
  - Visual landmarks.
  - *Sun-azimuth orientation* (requires internal clock).
  - *Star patterns* (North Star axis).
  - *Magnetic field* (magnetite in head/neck).

