= Social Behavior and Reproduction

- *Sociality*: Flocking for protection, migration, or feeding (e.g., pelicans).

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-27-22").path, width: 80%),
  caption: images.at("figure-27-22").caption
)

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-27-23").path, width: 80%),
  caption: images.at("figure-27-23").caption
)

- *Reproduction*:
  - Testes enlarge seasonally.
  - Females: Only left ovary/oviduct functional.
  - Fertilization in upper oviduct; albumin and shell added later.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-27-24").path, width: 80%),
  caption: images.at("figure-27-24").caption
)

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-27-25").path, width: 80%),
  caption: images.at("figure-27-25").caption
)

- *Mating Systems*:
  - *Monogamy*: Common (>90%). Both parents care for young.
  - *Polygyny*: One male, many females (e.g., grouse in *leks*).
  - *Polyandry*: One female, many males (rare, e.g., spotted sandpipers).

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-27-26").path, width: 80%),
  caption: images.at("figure-27-26").caption
)

- *Nesting and Young*:
  - *Altricial*: Naked, helpless at birth (e.g., songbirds).
  - *Precocial*: Down-covered, active at birth (e.g., ducks, quail).

